    <m:mn>238</m:mn></m:mrow>
  </m:msup>
  <m:mtext>U</m:mtext></m:mrow>
</m:math>  to fission, part of what allows thermonuclear bombs to be so large.</para><figure id="Figure_22_04_Bomb"><media id="fs-id1167066774517" alt="The figure shows schematic of a fusion bomb, in the shape of a closed cylinder. The outer portion has reflector and fission material and the inner portion has Styrofoam with gamma absorbers. The Styrofoam contains the shape charges, beryllium neutron reflector, lithium deuteride and the plutonium and uranium."><image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/CNX_HSPhysics_22_04_Bomb.jpg"/></media>

<caption>This schematic of a fusion bomb (H-bomb) gives some idea of how the  <m:math>
